Index
.................

Think of the index in a book.

Without an index: You read every page to find a topic.
With an index: You go directly to the required page.

A database index works the same way.

Syntax

Create Index

CREATE INDEX index_name
ON Employee(emp_id);

Create Unique Index

CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_email
ON Employee(email);

Show Index (MySQL)
.....................

SHOW INDEX FROM Employee;


Drop Index

DROP INDEX idx_email
ON Employee;



# Types of Indexes
.......
#1. Primary Index..
..........................
# Automatically created for the primary key.

CREATE TABLE Employee (
    emp_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    emp_name VARCHAR(50)
);

# No need to create it manually.



2. Unique Index
...................
Prevents duplicate values.

CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_email
ON Employee(email);
Valid
sunil@gmail.com
anil@gmail.com
Invalid
sunil@gmail.com
sunil@gmail.com

Duplicate values are not allowed.


3. Composite Index
,.........................
Created on multiple columns.

CREATE INDEX idx_dept_salary
ON Employee(dept_id, salary);

Useful for queries like:

SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE dept_id=1
AND salary>50000;



1. Clustered Index
........................................

A Clustered Index stores the actual table data in the order of the indexed column.

The table rows are physically sorted.

Only one clustered index can exist per table because data can be physically ordered only one way.

Example (SQL Server)
CREATE TABLE Employee (
    emp_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    emp_name VARCHAR(50),
    salary DECIMAL(10,2)
);

When you create a PRIMARY KEY, SQL Server creates a Clustered Index by default( sae data sorted manaer) (unless specified otherwise).

Employee Table
emp_id	emp_name	salary
101	Sunil	50000
102	Anil	60000
103	Ravi	70000
104	Kumar	55000

The rows are physically stored in emp_id order.

Searching:
..............................
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE emp_id = 103;

The database quickly reaches the correct location because the data itself is ordered.

Real-Time Banking Example
..............................
Account Table
.......................................
account_no	customer	balance
1001	Sunil	50000
1002	Anil	70000
1003	Ravi	30000

Create:
....................................
CREATE CLUSTERED INDEX idx_account
ON Account(account_no);

Searching:

SELECT *
FROM Account
WHERE account_no = 1002;

The database directly locates the record.

2. Non-Clustered Index
...................................
A Non-Clustered Index is a separate data structure.
....................
It stores:

Indexed column values
A pointer (row locator) to the actual table row

The table data is not physically reordered.

A table can have multiple non-clustered indexes.

Example

CREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX idx_name
ON Employee(emp_name);

Searching:

SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE emp_name='Sunil';

The database:
...............
Index
...........
Sunil  --------> Row 101

Anil   --------> Row 102

Ravi   --------> Row 103

It first finds "Sunil" in the index, then follows the pointer to retrieve the full row from the table.

Real-Time E-Commerce Example
.........................................
Product Table
.............................
product_id	product_name	price
101	Laptop	50000
102	Mouse	1000
103	Keyboard	2000

Create index:
.............................
CREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX idx_product_name
ON Product(product_name);

Search:

SELECT *
FROM Product
WHERE product_name='Laptop';

The index quickly finds "Laptop" and points to the corresponding table row.

